{{About||the mapping of constellations into quadrants|quadrant (astronomy)|the [[Star Trek]] terminology|Galactic quadrant (Star Trek)}}

[[File:Galactic longitude.JPG|thumb|300px|Longitudinal lines of the [[galactic coordinate system]].]]

A '''galactic quadrant''', or '''quadrant of the galaxy''', refers to one of four [[circular sector]]s in the division of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy.

==Quadrants in the galactic coordinate system==
{{Main|galactic coordinate system}}
In actual astronomical practice, the delineation of the galactic quadrants is based upon the [[galactic coordinate system]], which places the [[Sun]] as the [[polar coordinates|pole of the mapping system]]. The Sun is used instead of the [[galactic center]] for practical reasons since all astronomical observations (by [[human]]s) to date have been based on [[Earth]] or within the [[solar system]].

===Delineation===
Quadrants are described using [[Ordinal number (linguistics)|ordinals]]<U+2014>for example, "1<sup>st</sup> galactic quadrant"<ref name=toolsofradio>Thomas L. Wilson, Kristen Rohlfs, Susanne H<U+00FC>ttemeister [http://books.google.com/books?id=9KHw6R8rQEMC&pg=PA347&dq=%221st+galactic+quadrant%22&hl=en&ei=lOBlTKLNN4WClAePjd2IDQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%221st%20galactic%20quadrant%22&f=false ''Tools of radio astronomy'']</ref> "second galactic quadrant,"<ref name=NASAAD131K>{{cite web|url=http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2004A%26A...418..131K |title=NASA Astrophysics Data - Far-infrared loops in the 2nd Galactic Quadrant |publisher=Adsabs.harvard.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref> or "third quadrant of the Galaxy."<ref name=Lampton1997>M. Lampton ''et al''. [http://iopscience.iop.org/0067-0049/108/2/545 An All-Sky Catalog of Faint Extreme Ultraviolet Sources] ''The Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series ''. 1997</ref> Viewing from the [[north galactic pole]] with 0 [[degree (angle)|degree]]s (<U+00B0>) as the [[Line (mathematics)#Ray|ray]] that runs starting from the Sun and through the galactic center, the quadrants are as follow:
*1<sup>st</sup> galactic quadrant <U+2014> 0<U+00B0> <U+2264> [[galactic longitude|longitude]] (<U+2113>) <U+2264> 90<U+00B0><ref>''[http://www.astron.nl/~leeuwen/video/dloo/JAHH9p3.pdf THE BEGINNINGS OF RADIO ASTRONOMY IN THE NETHERLANDS].'' Journal of Astronomical History and Heritage. 2006</ref>
* 2<sup>nd</sup> galactic quadrant <U+2014> 90<U+00B0> <U+2264> <U+2113> <U+2264> 180<U+00B0><ref name=NASAAD131K/>
* 3<sup>rd</sup> galactic quadrant <U+2014> 180<U+00B0> <U+2264> <U+2113> <U+2264> 270<U+00B0><ref name=Lampton1997/>
* 4<sup>th</sup> galactic quadrant <U+2014> 270<U+00B0> <U+2264> <U+2113> <U+2264> 360<U+00B0> (0<U+00B0>)<ref name=toolsofradio />

===Visibility of each quadrant===
{{See also|List of celestial bodies in each galactic quadrant}}
[[File:Celestial.gif|right|thumb|Orientation of the galactic, [[Ecliptic coordinate system|ecliptic]] and [[equatorial coordinate system]]s, projected on the [[celestial sphere]].]]

Due to the orientation of the Earth with respect to the rest of the galaxy, the 2<sup>nd</sup> galactic quadrant is primarily only visible from the [[northern hemisphere]] while the 4<sup>th</sup> galactic quadrant is mostly only visible from the [[southern hemisphere]]. Thus, it is usually more practical for [[Amateur astronomy|amateur stargazers]] to use the [[Quadrant (astronomy)|celestial quadrants]]. Nonetheless, cooperating or international astronomical organizations are not so bound by the Earth's [[horizon]].

Based on a view from Earth, one may look towards major [[constellation]]s for a rough sense of where the borders of the quadrants are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thinkastronomy.com/M13/Manual/common/galactic_coords.html |title=Galactic Coordinates |publisher=Thinkastronomy.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref> (Note: by drawing a line through the following, one can also approximate the [[Galactic coordinate system#Definition|galactic equator]].)
* For 0<U+00BA>, look towards the [[Sagittarius (constellation)|Sagittarius]] constellation. (The galactic center)
* For 90<U+00BA>, look towards the [[Cygnus (constellation)|Cygnus]] constellation.
* For 180<U+00BA>, look towards the [[Auriga (constellation)|Auriga]] constellation. (The [[galactic anticenter]])
* For 270<U+00BA>, look towards the [[Vela (constellation)|Vela]] constellation.

==Traditional fourfold divisions of the skies==
{{Expand section|date=August 2010}}

A long tradition of dividing the visible skies into four precedes the modern definitions of four galactic quadrants. Ancient Mesopotamian formulae spoke of "the four corners of the universe" and of "the heaven's four corners",<ref>
{{Citation
 | last = Michalowski
 | first = Piotr
 | year = 2010
 | contribution = masters of the Four Corners of the Heavens: Vies of the Universe in Early Mesopotamian Writings
 | editor-last = Raaflaub
 | editor-first = Kurt A.
 | editor-link = Kurt Raaflaub
 | editor2-last = Talbert
 | editor2-first = Richard J. A.
 | editor2-link = Richard Talbert
 | title = Geography and Ethnography: Perceptions of the World in Pre-Modern Societies
 | edition =
 | series = The ancient world--comparative histories
 | publisher = John Wiley and Sons
 | volume = 3
 | pages = 147<U+2013>168
 | page = 153
 | isbn = 9781405191463
 | url = http://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=FH3WolaD9asC
}}
</ref>
and the Biblical [[Book of Jeremiah]] echoes this phraseology: "And upon Elam will I bring the four winds from the four quarters of heaven" (Jeremiah,  49:36). [[Astrology]] too uses [[House (astrology)#Quadrant House Systems|quadrant system]]s to divide up its stars of interest. And the astronomy of the location of [[constellation]]s sees each of the Northern and Southern [[celestial hemisphere]]s divided into four [[quadrant (astronomy)|quadrant]]s.

==Appearances in fiction==
=== ''Star Trek'' ===
{{see also|List of Star Trek regions of space#Galactic Quadrants}}
"Galactic quadrants" within ''[[Star Trek]]'' are based around a [[Meridian (astronomy)|meridian]] that runs from the center of the galaxy through Earth's [[solar system]],<ref name="Encyc">{{cite book|title=[[The Star Trek Encyclopedia]]|first=Michael|last=Okuda|authorlink=Michael Okuda|coauthors=Denise Okuda and Debbie Mirek|publisher=[[Pocket Books]]|isbn=0-671-53609-5|year=1999}}</ref> which is not unlike the system used by astronomers. However, rather than have the [[perpendicular]] [[Cartesian coordinate system|axis]] run through the Sun, as is done in astronomy, the ''Star Trek'' version runs the axis through the galactic center. In that sense, the ''Star Trek'' quadrant system is less-[[geocentric]] as a [[cartographical]] system than the standard. Also, rather than use ordinals, ''Star Trek'' designates them by the [[Greek alphabet|Greek]] letters [[Alpha (letter)|Alpha]], [[Beta (letter)|Beta]], [[Gamma]], and [[Delta (letter)|Delta]].

The [[Canadian]] Galactic Plane Survey (CGPS) created a [[Radio astronomy|radio]] map based on the galaxy based on ''Star Trek''{{'}}s quadrants, joking that "the CGPS is primarily concerned with [[Cardassia]], while the SGPS focuses on [[Romulans]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ras.ucalgary.ca/CGPS/where/plan/ |title=The Canadian Galactic Plane Survey - Plan Views of the Milky Way Galaxy |publisher=Ras.ucalgary.ca |date= |accessdate=2010-08-19}}</ref>

